onio Costa|series=Routledge Studies in Fascism and the Far Right|location=New York and London|pages=268|language=en|chapter=Corporatism and Authoritarianism in the Baltics: P\u00e4ts' Estonia in Comparison}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Johan Nygaardsvold]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{Flag|Norway}}\n|[[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |9 April 1940\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[German occupation of Norway|Occupation of Norway]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Prime Minister Nygaardsvold and King Haakon VII would continue to lead the [[Nygaardsvold's Cabinet|Norwegian government-in-exile]], and would be restored to power after the [[Liberation of Finnmark]] and [[Operation Doomsday]].\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TzOxCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA154&dq=April+1940+Johan+Nygaardsvold#v=onepage&q=April%201940%20Johan%20Nygaardsvold&f=false|title=Heads of State and Government|last=Da Gra\u00e7a|first=John V.|publisher=Springer|year=1985|isbn=9781349079995|location=London|pages=154|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkelDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA388&dq=April+1940+german+occupied+norway+haakon+vii&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfioPOqOLhAhVphosKHeE1AFcQ6AEIXDAJ#v=onepage&q=April%201940%20german%20occupied%20norway%20haakon%20vii&f=false|title=A Monetary History of Norway, 1816\u20132016|last=Eitrheim|first=\u00d8yvind|last2=Klovland|first2=Jan Tore|last3=\u00d8ksendal|first3=Lars Fredrik|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2016|isbn=9781107150409|location=Cambridge and New York|pages=388|language=en|chapter=The Extreme Liquidity Creation during the Occupation years, 1940 - 1945}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Haakon VII of Norway|Haakon VII]]\n|[[King of Norway]]\n|-\n|[[Charlotte, Grand Duchess of Luxembourg|Charlotte]]\n|rowspan=2|{{flag|Luxembourg}} \n|[[Grand Duchess of Luxembourg]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n|rowspan=2|  10 May 1940\n|rowspan=2|[[German invasion of Luxembourg|Occupation of Luxembourg]]\n| ro