nia}}\n|[[Prime Minister of Armenia]]\n|2 December 1920\n|[[Red Army invasion of Armenia]]\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ub2DrB95gXgC&pg=PA249&dq=1920+Simon+Vratsian#v=onepage&q=1920%20Simon%20Vratsian&f=false|title=Children of Armenia: A Forgotten Genocide and the Century-long Struggle for Justice|last=Bobelian|first=Michael|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=2009|isbn=9781416558354|location=New York|pages=50|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Noe Zhordania]]\n|{{Flag|Democratic Republic of Georgia|name=Georgia}}\n|[[Prime Minister of Georgia|Chairman of Georgia]]\n|18 March 1921\n|[[Red Army invasion of Georgia]]\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XMQTAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&dq=1920+Noe+Zhordania#v=snippet&q=1921%20Noe%20Jordania&f=false|title=The Making of Modern Georgia, 1918-2012: The First Georgian Republic and its Successors|last=Jones|first=Stephen F.|publisher=Routledge|year=2014|isbn=9781317815938|location=London and New York|pages=xvii|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QwquCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA470&dq=18+March+1921+Noe+Zhordania#v=onepage&q=18%20March%201921%20Noe%20Zhordania&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of the Russian Civil Wars, 1916-1926|last=Smele|first=Jonathan D.|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2015|isbn=9781442252813|location=Lanham, MA|pages=470|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Haile Selassie I]]\n|{{Flag|Ethiopia|1897}}\n|[[Emperor of Ethiopia]]\n|{{Flag|Kingdom of Italy|1861|name=Fascist Italy}}\n|2 May 1936\n|[[Second Italo-Ethiopian War|Occupation of Ethiopia]]\n|Selassie would be restored to power in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]] of World War II after a period of exile in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[United Kingdom]].\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WU92d6sB8JAC&pg=PA228&dq=1+May+1936+Haile+Selassie#v=onepage&q=1%20May%201936%20Haile%20Selassie&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of Ethiopia|last=Shinn|first=David H.|last2=Ofcansky|f