ory in Hungary|last=Benziger|first=Karl P.|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2010|isbn=9780739146279|location=Lamham, Boulder, New York, Toronto, Plymouth, UK|pages=1|language=en|orig-year=2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gc2NAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA790&dq=imre+nagy+encyclopedia#v=onepage&q=imre%20nagy%20encyclopedia&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of the Developing World|last=Held|first=Joseph|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=9781135205089|editor-last=Leonard|editor-first=Thomas M.|location=New York and London|pages=790|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tenzin Gyatso]]\n|{{Flag|Tibet}}\n|[[14th Dalai Lama]]\n|{{Flag|China}}\n|30 March 1959\n|[[1959 Tibetan uprising|Tibetan uprising]]\n|Following the unsuccessful uprising of 1959, the Dalai Lama was forced to flee to India, where set up a [[Government in exile|government-in-exile]] \n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lPdgDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA194&dq=dalai+lama+encyclopedia#v=onepage&q=dalai%20lama%20encyclopedia&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Buddhism, Robert E. Busswell, 2004: Encyclopedia of Buddhism|last=Platoff|first=Anne M.|publisher=Bukupedia|year=2003|isbn=978-0-7864-4593-6|editor-last=Song|editor-first=Yuwu|location=Jefferson, NC and London|pages=86|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lPdgDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA194&dq=dalai+lama+encyclopedia#v=onepage&q=dalai%20lama%20encyclopedia&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Buddhism, Robert E. Busswell, 2004: Encyclopedia of Buddhism|last=Sparham|first=Gareth|publisher=Bukupedia|year=2004|isbn=978-0-02-865719-6|editor-last=Buswell|editor-first=Robert E.|location=New York and Farmington Hill, MI|pages=195|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Francisco Caama\u00f1o]]\n|{{flag|Dominican Republic}}\n|[[Presidents of the Dominican Republic|President of the Dominican Republic]]\n|{{flag|United States}}\n|3 September 1965\n|[[U.S. invasion of the Dominican Republic]]\n|Caama\u00f1o was one of the leaders in the movement to restore the democratically